segments.text: When it comes to raising your children.
That's not being a dud.
Did y'all make some close friends in Austin?
We got along real well with his employees.
And we, Dr. Ashworth.
He was there, of course, one of Jack's.
But in two years, you don't get that involved in a big city with your husband traveling all over the state.
But life wasn't dull.
We were involved in things, but we never were really, as far as the city was concerned, that involved in anything.
I went to the church.
I belonged to a woman's group, but I wasn't working at it.
And if you don't work at something, you're not part of it.
Now, were those Texans receptive to Carolinians, Virginians moving there?
Were you all treated courteously in Austin?
Sure.
I don't think that... That was a cosmopolitan city.
I don't think there's any problem there.
Right.
And then you went to Tennessee, and you all lived in Knoxville?
Mm-hmm.
Describe Andy Holt.
His character.
Everybody loved him.
He had a charming way of being around people.
And do you know that after we moved, that he would take Mary fishing?
When his wife went to her club, he would take Mary out to fish.
Then he would go and dress the fish for her.
After we left, he was...
He just was a lovable personality as far as I'm concerned and successful in what he did.
As head of the University of Tennessee system, I have often thought that in many ways Jack Kenny Williams and the way he went about things was similar to Andy Holt in the way he went about things.
Would you agree with that?
They both had good senses of humor?
Well, they weren't the type to push their weight around.
They both had a way of... Jack had a way of getting things done without being abrasive, don't you think?
Yes, didn't Dr. Holt?
Well, of course, I wasn't that close to Dr. Holt in two years, you know, to know, but he was liked and loved as far as I'm concerned, and I didn't know his enemies.
Everybody has them.
Everybody makes them.
But both Williams and Holt
When I saw them publicly, they had a good sense of humor when it was time to be humorous and a very good sense of seriousness when it was time to be serious.
And neither one of them would talk about the unpleasant.
Jack didn't talk about the unpleasant things.
You never heard him talk about the people on the board that were not cooperative with anything he wanted.
You never heard him talk about it, did you?
No, no.

I think that there are ways to get things done, and I don't know how Jack did it, but he got things done because he would just sort of say this is what we need to do and work at it and get someone to help.
He used people.
You felt used, didn't you?
Like you did about putting together the... No, I always thought the assignments were very appropriate.
But you were never ignored.
Oh, no.
Very true.
That you were part of the team.
That's right.
He worked with you.
I shouldn't say used you, but he worked with the team.
Very much so.
When you all came to A&M, when did you first see the House, the President's House?
Did you all come to visit before he accepted?
I was there with the Rutters when he was commissioner of higher education.
So you had been... Margaret had, while Jack was there for a meeting, she asked Governor Conley to come by and meet me, and he did.
He came by the house and met me and the two girls.
Just briefly.
Let's digress on...
But I didn't go up and look in the clauses or anything like that.
Describe your impression of John Conley.
describe what kind of governor did he seem to be?
I thought he was a successful governor and a leader that he got.
He and Margaret Rutter were in school together.
They were good friends.
I don't think that I was in the position to evaluate him as the governor of Texas pro or con.
I wasn't that involved with it.
I think you overrate me for thinking that I would know.

But he was an influence in bringing Jack back to Texas A&M when a member of the board, and I don't remember which one of them I heard to say this, that they went to John Connolly to check on Jack because he'd been commissioner, and he said, get him if you can.
Now, that's an important fact for us to record.
I learned, by the way, not long ago from Mrs. Rutter, when I referred to Nellie Connolly, that that really wasn't her name.
And I said, oh, and she said her name was Milda, I believe Milda May, all one word.
But that when... Ida Nell.
Ida Nell.
Ida Nell, there's a song.
But that then when he was running for governor, one of the campaign managers said that that sounded not as
as upbeat as Nellie.
So that she said, all of us knew her as Ida Nell, but the reporters called her Nellie.
When you all arrived at the campus, was there any furniture in the house?
Yes.
And how did your furniture fit into them?
Well, I gave most of my furniture to Margaret Rudder.
for a period of time.
I took my furniture and furnished Mary's bedroom and her sitting room upstairs.
So she had family furniture in those two rooms.
And the rest of it either went in the store or to the Rutter's house.
Margaret had not bought furniture.
See, she'd been living in a furnished house.
And I hadn't.
I had my own secondhand stuff.
But I felt like Mary deserved to have only family furniture in her two rooms, which is what I did.
And the rest of it now, I had in one bedroom, I had an antique bed that my granddaddy cut down the tree and had
made for his wedding bed, and my granddaughter has it now.
I put that in one room, and I put another bed that I'm sleeping in right now in another bedroom upstairs.
I guess those bedrooms weren't furnished, or weren't totally furnished.
There may have been something in their rooms.
But I remember I had two of my beds upstairs, and they had a king-size bed.
in the master bedroom.
And I can't remember where I made that, finally made that into two twin beds or what I did, but anyway it was, I just sort of adjusted what we needed and what we had.
And then later on I sent from Margaret, I got back the sofa that's in the living room to put in Jack's office because they had a little plastic type sofa in there that wasn't very nice.
And turn it off, and I'll tell you an interesting story.
When you got to the campus, what kind of staffing was there for the president's home?
Was there a full-time employee?
Well, yeah.
This I can't put in.
I had Willie, a black man that had been the chauffeur for the Rutter children and the bartender.
And Juanita had left with Margaret, that was the cook.
And they brought a lady over that couldn't even set up a tea tray.
And she was a minister's daughter, I mean a wife.
Is this on?
You want me to turn it on?
Who were, in your College Station years, who were the favorite friends of the Williams?
Who did you all enjoy most as friends?
We never invited people into the house at night unless there was some special occasion.
When Jack came home, what times he was home at night, I never added to his evenings unless it was something unusual.
We never had, like the Rudders did, a group of people that came to the house to party.
We never had that.
I probably wonder now if the people on his staff didn't wonder why aren't we ever invited to dinner at their house.
You weren't.
Because the schedule was so demanding, I know.
I never added.
We never had.
He once asked me to let him invite the children of his friends over to entertain them for meals, and I said, no, you'll make more enemies than you make friends because you'll forget somebody.
You'll overlook people.
And that will just, if we're right here, everybody can see the comings and going.
And I enjoyed a lot of people, but...
As I said, we didn't.
You know that from experience.
You weren't invited there.
I did what I had to do, but I just didn't add to anything that was not scheduled.
Right.
So y'all were not part of a bridge group or a bridge group there?
No, no.
We weren't part of a social group at all that I know of.
We got along with everybody and enjoyed everybody, but...
This sounds awful for me, but I just didn't invite people to add to anything that he had to do.
I felt like he needed some time to relax.
Sure.
When you all went on vacation while you were in California?
We looked for a place where nobody knew us.
Where did you go?
Do you remember?
Yeah, we went to Callaway Gardens.
We went to High Hampton.
We went to visit the families.
We went to Canada once.
Did I tell you about Canada?
No.

uh we were oh i found out i could have turned this off i'm trying to think of the name of this place i think we were there and jack said quick quick mary was with us and he pointed out that there was a whole carload of aggies unloading
So we went in a jewelry store and stayed a while.
Isn't that mean?
No, he didn't need to get involved when you're away.
He just needed some time for us.
During those A&M years, who were the state and federal legislators that were most helpful to Dr. Williams and to A&M?
Who was there in Austin and Washington that was?
I don't know.
I know that he had one friend that was a budget board man.
On the LBB?
The budget board.
He came to see him once.
Did I tell you about that?
No.
Joe, will you go in the office and take the picture of the steer down and bring it in here on the wall?
One day this man shows up at the office.
And he was in motorcycle clothes.
He came on a motorcycle.
And he wanted to go in there and see that president.
And Hilary Gaines, worked for Jack, said, do you have an appointment?
No, but I'm going in there to see that president.
And of course she didn't know who he was.

so but she said you can't go and she got up and stood in front of the door and blocked it and of course neil colwell's his name i think oh i remember that name we're looking at a big uh looks like red angus bull
And this is a drawing which Mr. Caldwell made.
Look at that.
Isn't that awful?
Did he present that work of art to Dr. Williams?
No, not then, but another time.
But he went in and, of course, was very amused to think that Jack would have somebody that loyal to him working in an office.
But Hillary literally got up and put her arms across the door and wouldn't let him go in.
And I guess that's when he told her who he was.
But he was the budget boy.
That is the steer for the King Ranch.
Sired the King Ranch.
Don't you think that's interesting?
Oh, yeah.
That he thought that much of Jack, that he would give him one of his art pieces.
No, I don't...
I don't know...
What about Tiger Teague?
Do you remember him?
Oh, yeah, Tiger Teague was a great help, and Catherine went to work for him in Washington after she graduated.
Tiger Teague and Jack were friends, but I never knew what was going on as far as the business of the university and who you were picking up and calling.
I saw Jack one time be called

by somebody at the university and asking him to see if they could save the permanent fund did i tell you that before they couldn't get one of the members of the legislature in dallas they could they said they this is the reason i hate this they couldn't get to him could he could he did he think he could get him to vote for them to save the permanent that's when all the colleges wanted to break it down
And Jack said, sure.
So he picked up the telephone and called the head of the frozen food expense, Stubbs, and told him what the problem was.
And he said, yes, we own him.
Did you cut that off?
No, we can work that out later.
We own him.
And five minutes later, he got the phone call saying that it was all taken care of.
But the University of Texas was a strong political group.
You realize that always.
They were used to having their way regardless of what it was and what was going on.
And Dr. Williams and Mickey LeMaitre, who was then the chancellor of the UT system, they were old acquaintances.
They were friends, always were.
And worked well together, didn't they?
Mm-hmm.
He's the one that called Jack that day about coming to the medical center, and that was on a Monday, and the next Monday we were down there for a business meeting with members of the hospital board.
I'm not going to ask you the negative on this one.
Of the A&M board members, who were his favorites?
Mr. Zachary would be one, wouldn't he?
He wasn't on the board.
Oh, he was off the board by then?
Yeah.
Okay.
He was on the coordinating board.
You know what Mr. Zachary told me?
What's that?
I shouldn't repeat it.
He told me Jack was the finest man he ever knew.
He talked to him every week.
That's the kind of thing we do want on there.
To me, that...
I taught my children what respect was by using Mr. Zachary.
I told them that you have to respect the source of your criticism, pro or con, and that Mr. Zachary's criticism, any way it came, we would sure pay attention to it.
We respected him.
And I think that's a good way to have a good example to teach a child.
Right.
Now, if we were listing...
I don't know.
He had good friends on the board.
And I had some wives that were good friends.
Who?
Which ones?
I have a letter.
I don't know what I did with it.
He came to see us when he was in the hospital, too, in Dallas.
They both died close together.
She wrote me a letter once that said,
Where do you all have to be?
Goodson.
Goodson.
Goodson.
Goodson.
Joe can remember.
She was a good friend of mine, and he was a good friend.
He got along okay.
Now, as I say, Jack and I were not the buddy-buddy type people.
The only person I know that he was over in former students, I think he could relax and be silly over there with the people that worked for him.
They were such good friends and worked so hard for their university, and they weren't political.
With Buck Wirus and Dick Hervey?
Yeah, those people over there.
But, see, we were not buddy-buddy people.
I'm still not.
I have good friends, but I've just always gone for, this goes back to my childhood.
I'm sure that you always have a best friend, but that you don't live together.
You know what I'm saying is you don't have to have, you don't have to have somebody around.
I'll bet you all are that way.
You don't have to have somebody in the house every night.
What were his favorite foods when you were going to feed him?
What?
What was his favorite food?
What did he enjoy most?
Well, what we had the most were Williamsburgers.
What's a Williamsburger?
Yes.
A hamburger.
But what made it a Williamsburger?
It was made by Jack Williams.
He could put, even at the last years of our life,
We were going to have a hamburger, which we had our meat special ground for.
It wasn't a hamburger.
We went to the butcher and had him grind our meat.
Jack had put one together that was juicy and delicious and just wonderful, and he had his own recipe, which he put egg in his hamburgers.
But one of my nieces named them Williamsburgers and we always had Williamsburgers.
Now what else went on the Williamsburger other than meat?
Lettuce and tomato.
We'd have lettuce and tomato, nothing else.
No onions ever.
Mayonnaise.
But mustard went in the making of Williamsburgers.
Mustard, egg, and salt went in the making of Williamsburgers.
Right.
Let's make believe that you know he's going to have a long, tiresome day, and you want to feed him an evening meal that you know he'll really enjoy.
What would you have served?
No telling.
We ate normal food and balanced meals.
I still have a balanced meal.
Every meal for myself is a balanced meal because that's your health.
And I tried to take care of Jack.
Jack had health problems before we ever heard of Texas.
And so, I mean, I...

I bought sirloin tip roasts and we had potatoes and we had, you know, another dish that was easy and it's off my diet now was open a can of baked beans, pork and beans, pour a lot of ketchup on top and onion slices all over the top and bake it.
Now, that was an old standby.
Homemade applesauce.
We had a lot of applesauce.
We had a lot of cabbage slaw.
We never cooked cabbage.
You know, it's just good old...
Were there some foods that you knew he didn't like?
It's been so long, he wasn't a complainer.
He finally didn't like apricot bread.
Whatever he did like was so routine that I just never had to give a great thought to anything.
I fed my children vegetables and good meat.
Oh, back in those days we had a lot of fried chicken.
Remember when fried chicken was okay to eat?
And I was real good at that.
But now I barbecue outside chicken thighs.
which is the difference you see in the way we cook now, what we did then.
But it was okay then to have fried chicken, and that was good.
How long has it been since you fried chicken?
About 20 years.
Did he have some favorite desserts?
This is interesting to me that you wanted to know these details.
We're trying to learn.
See, we want to learn all we can about the person.
Uh-huh.
There was always ice cream and Ms. McCauley's Pound Cake.
This is a recipe for a pound cake that Hugh McCauley's mother made.
And that's the reason it was called Ms. McCauley's Pound Cake.
But no, Jack just didn't require a lot of anything because we...
Things just agreed on between us.
We didn't say Jack Spratt could eat no fat and his wife could eat no lean.
We didn't do like that.
Whatever was there was there.
He cooked breakfast a lot of the times for us, for the girls and so forth.
He got home first.
He cooked dinner if I was out taking a child to orthodontist or something like that.
He came home
He didn't sit down and wait for me to come home.
He cooked a lot of meals.
My wife was asking me if I was listening to that.
Well, this was because he had a working mother.
He had a working mother, and he didn't sit around and wait for her.
In fact, he used to have to go to the drugstore and let his mother go home for supper, and he ran the drugstore while his parents went home to eat.
And then he had to be back.
at 9.30 to help them close.

Jack was a person who had every hour of his day, even as a young man, programmed with school and he participated in things, you know, and played football and helped with the drug store and had a paper route in the morning.
He was brought up to be programmed by the hour.
And I told you the last time about his mother saying she cried when she had to bundle him up and send him out in this terrible weather to deliver his papers.
And when he told me about it, his was a different story.
I just tried to be in a certain place on the hill to see the sun come up, and then one of his customers always had him in for a cup of hot chocolate.
So he was, you know, he had a good youth with a very strict father.
And I think all this program showed.
This is why he never...
complained about things.
He just kept it all to himself if it was bad.
As that while he was president of A&M with that very demanding schedule where did he keep his his daily schedule?
Was it in a little book as I have mine?
There was there something he carried in his pocket?
I have those all in a drawer.
Okay and so he would check that if someone asked him about can you come to this kind of a meeting he would check that little
I don't know.
He had his schedule and little tiny writing in them.
And sometimes I have one matchbook where he took notes at a meeting.
I wanted to send it to Dick Linerty.
It's still back there in my desk drawer, the matchbook where he took notes at a meeting.
And it was something about the medical center, planning for the medical center.
So evidently he was...
That's what he had to write in was that matchbook, and that's where he wrote them.
And it was in his desk drawer, and it still is.
It's hard to describe Jack because he could...
I told him, just turn it off.
Let me turn this back on.
How did you all meet John Lindsay?
Do you remember when you first became acquainted with John and Sarah Lindsay?
No, I don't.
As I told you, we weren't... See, even the people that came after football games and so forth were lots of times people that I hardly knew.
We were invited to the Lindsay's once in Houston to dinner, and we got there real... See, it came through John to Jack, and nothing in writing, no phone call from her.
And we showed up too early.
And so she made it clear that she had work to do in order to cook for us.
And we left and then came back.
She suggested that we come back or something like that.
But I just was pulled along, which I often was.
I never got on an airplane if Jack didn't have in writing an invitation for me.
When he went on the airplane, I was never there unless it was something that I was supposed to attend.
And I showed up then for that without any prior information.
Lots of times I did.
Recently, the Heisman Trophy Award that came to Walker while we were in it,
Houston while we were in College Station, remember Walker getting the Heisman winning.
I went to that banquet when he praised his mother and there were three tears of, I'd never heard of the Heisman Award.
I didn't know what I was at now and I've got a copy of it now out of that Texas A&M book.
I can't remember what tier I was sitting at, probably the lowest tier.
But the Maltz brothers, Melvin Maltz and his brother, were very involved in that Heisman Award that night.
And Walker gave great credit to his mother, as usual.
But until recently, I'd never known the background for the Heisman trophy.
Have you?
Not really.
and who Heisman was and so forth.
It's real interesting.
And it might even be right here where I can... Oh, I forget, I can't...
It might be pulled...
I tore it out of the paper.
It's right behind those books there, down there below.
Let's go back to John Lindsay.
He just was never a person not to just show up and help.
That's what he's still doing.
And, no, it'd be on the other stool back there.
I may have carried it back to the office, but anyway, I'll mail it to you.
I'll make a copy and mail it to you.
I just don't know when he came into my paying attention to him.
They were always nice people, but even at the reception last week for the press, they're just there.
He doesn't... She is...
I think a very involved person, but nothing pushy about her.
And he's just pushy about Texas A&M, as far as I know.
He's successful.
And they lost one of their sons.
And he was in the hospital when Jack was with his heart attack.
And I got John's birthday cake.
He sent a cake up to us, and I didn't know it.
And we took the cake.
Even though Catherine did wish she could have one piece, we took it up and gave it to the people that were taking care of Jack.
We gave his birthday cake away.
And then later on, he said he didn't get a birthday cake.
They asked for something.
I said, oh, we gave it away.
But their son had his back operation, and I went out and bought him a cactus, carried it in, which I thought was something for a young person, you know, to grow it.
